Reasoning: The paper develops a game-theoretic framework for studying competition between firms in a social network, which suggests that it belongs to the Game Theory (cs.GT), Social and Information Networks (cs.SI), and Social Computing (cs.SOC) sub-categories. The use of stochastic diffusion processes and the analysis of the Price of Anarchy and Budget Multiplier also suggest that it could belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) and Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA) sub-categories.
